<br>
First, they are called <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> &quot;Planar Abilities.&quot;</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> This suggests that they are at the very least obtained on the planes.<br>
<br>
Second, if they are usable everywhere, like ordinary spells, then what is the difference between <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> &quot;Planar Abilities&quot;</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> and <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> &quot;ordinary&quot;</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> spells?  They are activated, have effects, consume mana and components, but not, apparently, a space in my spell book.  If they are <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> &quot;spell-like skills,&quot;</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, like <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Manaburn, Dire Charm,</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> or <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Frenzied Burnout</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, then there sure are a lot of them.<br>
<br>
If the only difference between planar abilities and spells is how they are obtained, it seems like a whole lot effort for not much difference.  Once you had them, it would just be buttons to push.  True, they would not take spell gems....<br>
<br>
On the other hand, if they are effectively spells that are only activatable on the planes, then separating them out from spells as <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> &quot;planar abilities&quot;</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> makes a simple and clear distinction.<br>
<br>
Just speculation, mind you, but suggestive, at least to me.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Raz</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
